All workers became eligible to join trade unions, and to negotiate the terms and conditions of their employment. This fact has taken a lot of time to sink in, leading to unnecessarily adversarial labour relations.
Secondly, we must critically interrogate the role of the Salaries and Remuneration Commission (SRC). Over time, we have realised that the commission failed in its original constitutional mission to control the ability of State Officers (who are not eligible to join trade unions) to determine their own pay.
Indeed, the SRC was meant to be the State officer ‘employer’ on behalf of ‘the people’ collectively. The rest of our public officers would join trade unions and negotiate with their employers under the industrial relations regime introduced by the new constitution.
Unfortunately, the SRC has now abdicated from it constitutional responsibility to “set State officers’ pay and advise on other public officers pay”, and now purports to “advise on State officers’ pay and set other public officers’ pay”.
This deliberate misinterpretation of the constitution is at the heart of the reigning industrial unrest in Kenya. If SRC maintained the constitutional boundaries set for it, it would determine without contradiction the pay of our political class, and only provide economic implication advice to public sector employers who would then take full responsibility for their financial decisions.



